text:
Dear Ultraviolette,

The record you‚Äôve achieved with your electric motorcycle is certainly impressive, but as enthusiasts who ride superbikes for the thrill, the experience goes beyond just performance. It‚Äôs about the visceral connection‚Äîthe intake growl and the exhaust roar of an inline-4 or V4 engine. That raw, mechanical symphony is what we live for when riding motorcycles.
With electric motorcycles, however, that emotional connection feels absent. While I understand the appeal of electric technology, I genuinely believe that most motorcycle enthusiasts aren‚Äôt inclined to embrace electric superbikes because they lack the soul-stirring experience we associate with traditional engines.
Even in the world of hyper cars, while brands like Rimac have showcased remarkable electric innovation, car collectors and enthusiasts still gravitate toward icons like Koenigsegg, McLaren, or Ferrari for their emotional and sensory appeal. It would have been a proud moment for India if Ultraviolette, instead of focusing solely on electric, had developed a homegrown inline-4 or V4 performance engine‚Äîa true "Made in India" marvel. While I acknowledge how challenging it is to build a brand from the ground up, I feel an electric motorcycle just doesn‚Äôt capture the heart of a true motorcycle enthusiast.
